\date{2025-07-02}
\title{Archived: Synthetic Tiny objects}
\author{samueltoth}
\taxon{Module}
\import{stt-macros}

\subtree[stt-00KL]{
  \taxon{Warning}

  \p{This module is no longer in the library, but kept here as an
  archive.}
}

\subtree[stt-00B9]{
\taxon{Warning}
\p{This module uses some strong rewrite rules which I am not certain have semantic
justification, it is likely that it will be rewritten to a more orhodox foundation
in the future. Nonetheless the interface exposed in \ref{stt-00AA}
and \ref{stt-00AH} will hopefully remain intact.}
}

\subtree[stt-00BA]{
\taxon{Warning}
\p{Instantiating this module at a particular type axiomitises that the type
has an amazing right adjoint. There are types for which this is not sound.}
}

\agda{
\Keyword{open} \Keyword{import} \Module{[Foundations.Prelude](/html/Foundations.Prelude.html)}

\Keyword{module} \Module{[Archive.Synthetic.Tiny](Archive.Synthetic.Tiny)} \Symbol{\lbrace{}@}♭ \Bound{[𝓘](Archive.Synthetic.Tiny)}\Symbol{\rbrace{}} \Symbol{\lpar{}@}♭ \Bound{[I](Archive.Synthetic.Tiny)} \Symbol{:} \Primitive{[Type](Foundations.Universes)} \Bound{[𝓘](Archive.Synthetic.Tiny)}\Symbol{\rpar{}} \Keyword{where}

\Keyword{open} \Keyword{import} \Module{[Modalities.Cohesion.Flat](Modalities.Cohesion.Flat)}
\Keyword{open} \Keyword{import} \Module{[Axioms.UF](/html/Axioms.UF.html)}
}


\subtree[stt-00BC]{
\title{Internally Tiny Object}
\date{2025-11-17}
\taxon{Definition}

\p{In a cartesian closed category #{\CC}, for each object #{I}, there is an
adjunction #{- \times I \dashv -^I}. The object is called (internally)-\em{tiny}
or sometimes \em{atomic} if #{-^I} has a further right adjoint, which we will
call #{\sqrt[I]{-}}. This right adjoint is also referred to as \em{the amazing
right adjoint} - terminology which stems from synthetic differential geometry.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Idea}

\p{In type theory, we can represent the situation where a type #{I} has a right
adjoint using with the following judgement (Where #{\mathcal{P}} represents
exponentiating the context by #{I}):}

##{
\frac{\mathcal{P}(\Gamma) \vdash A}{\Gamma \vdash \sqrt[I]{A}}
}

\p{In addition, you need rules expressing the unit and counit of the adjunction.
It is clearly not possible to introduce this type as an axiom inside of type
theory; but there have been structural extensions to type theory that allow this
type to be represented. Firstly, it fits within the general framework of
[multimode type theory](GKNB21) and this approach is taken in \citek{GWB2024} to
define the category of spaces. Secondly, Mitchel Riley \citek{MR2024} introduced a
bespoke type theory that incorporates a tiny object.}

\p{Seperately, \citek{LOPS2018} make use of the [flat
modality](Modalities.Cohesion.Flat) to postulate an amazing right adjoint. In this
module we formalise a similar construction, except instead of postulating the
adjunction directly, we postulate a type former with #{\beta} and #{\eta} laws
roughly based off Mitchel Riley's work.  }
}

\subtree[stt-00AG]{
\taxon{Notation}

\p{We first define some notation that allows the posulated rules for the
[root type](stt-00A8) to appear close to how they would be presented in the
description of a type theory.}

\subtree{
\title{Technical remark}

\p{We make the substitution operation (which is just function composition)
opaque, so that we can make use of rewriting to make substitution commute with
new type formers definitionally. We prove functoriality of substitution inside
the opaque block, and then \em{re-expose} this computational behaviour using
rewrite rules.}
}

