\subtree[stt-00AH]{
\taxon{Construction}
\title{A universe that weakly classifies relative fibrations}

\p{We first fix a notion of fibrancy #{\mathcal{F}}, which is predicate on type
families, and ask that it is relative in the sense of \ref{stt-00AO}}

\p{From this we can define the notation of \em{amazing fibrancy}, which is a
predicate on a type - not a type family. Informally, amazing fibrancy says that
a type is fibrant over any arbitrary context.}

\p{The universe of fibrant types can then be defined to be the types which are
amazingly fibrant. There is a map #{\pi : \UU_{\mathcal{F}} \to \UU}, and
#{\UU_{\mathcal{F}}} is characterised by the property that a map #{A \to \UU}
factors through #{\pi} iff it is fibrant.}

